# BERT Training on Twitter Sentiment Dataset with PyQt GUI

## 1. Introduction
This assignment focuses on building a Twitter sentiment analysis system using a trained BERT model. The goal of the project is to classify tweets or manually entered text as Positive or Negative. A PyQt desktop GUI was developed so that the trained model can be used through a simple graphical interface.

The project follows the complete machine learning workflow: dataset cleaning, label conversion, model training, evaluation, model saving, model loading, and GUI-based prediction.

## 2. Dataset Description
The dataset used in this project is a Twitter sentiment dataset in CSV format. The important columns used from the dataset are `text` and `polarity`.

The `text` column contains the tweet, while the `polarity` column contains the sentiment label. The original labels were converted into binary labels for training.

| Original Polarity | Converted Label | Sentiment |
|---|---|---|
| 0 | 0 | Negative |
| 4 | 1 | Positive |

A balanced dataset was created by selecting an equal number of positive and negative tweets. This helps reduce model bias toward one class.

## 3. Dataset Preprocessing
The dataset preprocessing included the following steps:

- Loaded the CSV dataset using pandas
- Selected only useful columns
- Removed missing text values
- Converted polarity labels into numeric labels
- Balanced the dataset
- Saved the cleaned dataset as `twitter_sentiment_clean.csv`
- Generated a class distribution graph

The final cleaned dataset contained both Positive and Negative sentiment classes.

